Raw dev notes -- February 2026

Quick project that scratched a real itch. I use Google Recorder a lot -- it's great
for recording meetings and lectures because it transcribes in real-time and identifies
different speakers. The problem: there's no way to bulk export recordings. The web app
only lets you download one at a time, and I had dozens I needed for a transcription
project.

So I built a CLI tool in Node.js (commander.js) that authenticates with saved browser
credentials, lists all recordings, and batch-downloads the audio files along with
their speaker diarization data (who spoke when).

The interesting discovery was using accessibility tree snapshots instead of traditional
HTML parsing. Instead of writing CSS selectors to navigate the web app's DOM (which
changes frequently), I query the browser's accessibility tree. It gives you a clean,
structured view of the page content that's much more stable than the underlying HTML.
I'd used a11y trees for testing before but never thought to use them for data extraction.

Also integrated Chrome DevTools Protocol for development and debugging. Being able to
inspect the live page state while the script runs made development much faster.

This was a two-day project, but it's genuinely useful. The a11y snapshot approach is
something I'll probably use again -- it's a nice pattern for any tool that needs to
interact with web apps that don't have APIs.
